The first main.c is an example file that shows how multi-threading works in the in the Nordic SDK, and the next one is a working example of how dect nr+ works. how would I adapt the dect nr+ example to use multiple threads instead of just one loop? /*

 * Copyright (c) 2017 Linaro Limited

 *

 * SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0

#include <zephyr/kernel.h>

#include <zephyr/sys/printk.h>

#include <string.h>

// Define stack size used by each thread

#define THREAD0_STACKSIZE      512

#define THREAD1_STACKSIZE      512

#define WORQ_THREAD_STACK_SIZE 512


/* STEP 2 - Set the priorities of the threads */

#define THREAD0_PRIORITY 2

#define THREAD1_PRIORITY 3

#define WORKQ_PRIORITY     4


// Define stack area used by workqueue thread

static K_THREAD_STACK_DEFINE(my_stack_area, WORQ_THREAD_STACK_SIZE);


// Define queue structure

static struct k_work_q offload_work_q = {0};


/* STEP 5 - Define function to emulate non-urgent work */

static inline void emulate_work()

{

    for (volatile int count_out = 0; count_out < 150000; count_out++)

        ;

}


/* STEP 7 - Create work_info structure and offload function */

struct work_info {

    struct k_work work;

    char name[25];

} my_work;


void offload_function(struct k_work *work_tem)

{

    emulate_work();

}


void thread0(void)

{

    uint64_t time_stamp;

    int64_t delta_time;

    /* STEP 8 - Start the workqueue, */

    /* initialize the work item and connect it to its handler function */

    k_work_queue_start(&offload_work_q, my_stack_area, K_THREAD_STACK_SIZEOF(my_stack_area),

               WORKQ_PRIORITY, NULL);

    strcpy(my_work.name, "Thread0 emulate_work()");

    k_work_init(&my_work.work, offload_function);

    while (1) {

        time_stamp = k_uptime_get();

        /* STEP 9 - Submit the work item to the workqueue instead of calling emulate_work()

         * directly */

        /* Remember to comment out emulate_work(); */

        k_work_submit_to_queue(&offload_work_q, &my_work.work);

        delta_time = k_uptime_delta(&time_stamp);

        printk("thread0 yielding this round in %lld ms\n", delta_time);

        k_msleep(20);

    }

}


/* STEP 4 - Define entry function for thread1 */

void thread1(void)

{

    uint64_t time_stamp;

    int64_t delta_time;


    while (1) {

        time_stamp = k_uptime_get();

        emulate_work();

        delta_time = k_uptime_delta(&time_stamp);


        printk("thread1 yielding this round in %lld ms\n", delta_time);

        k_msleep(20);

    }

}


K_THREAD_DEFINE(thread0_id, THREAD0_STACKSIZE, thread0, NULL, NULL, NULL, THREAD0_PRIORITY, 0, 0);

K_THREAD_DEFINE(thread1_id, THREAD1_STACKSIZE, thread1, NULL, NULL, NULL, THREAD1_PRIORITY, 0, 0);

/* Send operation. */

static int transmit(uint32_t handle, void *data, size_t data_len)

{

    int err;


    struct phy_ctrl_field_common header = {

        .header_format = 0x0,

        .packet_length_type = 0x0,

        .packet_length = 0x01,

        .short_network_id = (CONFIG_NETWORK_ID & 0xff),

        .transmitter_id_hi = (device_id >> 8),

        .transmitter_id_lo = (device_id & 0xff),

        .transmit_power = CONFIG_TX_POWER,

        .reserved = 0,

        .df_mcs = CONFIG_MCS,

    };


    struct nrf_modem_dect_phy_tx_params tx_op_params = {

        .start_time = 0,

        .handle = handle,

        .network_id = CONFIG_NETWORK_ID,

        .phy_type = 0,

        .lbt_rssi_threshold_max = 0,

        .carrier = CONFIG_CARRIER,

        .lbt_period = NRF_MODEM_DECT_LBT_PERIOD_MAX,

        .phy_header = (union nrf_modem_dect_phy_hdr *)&header,

        .data = data,

        .data_size = data_len,

    };


    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_tx(&tx_op_params);

    if (err != 0) {

        return err;

    }


    return 0;

}


/* Receive operation. */

static int receive(uint32_t handle)

{

    int err;


    struct nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx_params rx_op_params = {

        .start_time = 0,

        .handle = handle,

        .network_id = CONFIG_NETWORK_ID,

        .mode = NRF_MODEM_DECT_PHY_RX_MODE_CONTINUOUS,

        .rssi_interval = NRF_MODEM_DECT_PHY_RSSI_INTERVAL_OFF,

        .link_id = NRF_MODEM_DECT_PHY_LINK_UNSPECIFIED,

        .rssi_level = -60,

        .carrier = CONFIG_CARRIER,

        .duration = CONFIG_RX_PERIOD_S * MSEC_PER_SEC *

                NRF_MODEM_DECT_MODEM_TIME_TICK_RATE_KHZ,

        .filter.short_network_id = CONFIG_NETWORK_ID & 0xff,

        .filter.is_short_network_id_used = 1,

        /* listen for everything (broadcast mode used) */

        .filter.receiver_identity = 0,

    };


    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx(&rx_op_params);

    if (err != 0) {

        return err;

    }


    return 0;

}

#define SLEEP_TIME_MS 1000


/* STEP 8 - Define the I2C slave device address and the addresses of relevant registers */

#define CTRLMEAS 0xF4

#define CALIB00  0x88

#define ID       0xD0

#define TEMPMSB  0xFA


#define CHIP_ID  0x60

#define SENSOR_CONFIG_VALUE 0x93


/* STEP 6 - Get the node identifier of the sensor */

#define I2C_NODE DT_NODELABEL(mysensor)


/* Data structure to store BME280 data */

struct bme280_data {

    /* Compensation parameters */

    uint16_t dig_t1;

    int16_t dig_t2;

    int16_t dig_t3;

} bmedata;



void bme_calibrationdata(const struct i2c_dt_spec *spec, struct bme280_data *sensor_data_ptr)

{

    /* Step 10 - Put calibration function code */

    uint8_t values[6];


    int ret = i2c_burst_read_dt(spec, CALIB00, values, 6);


    if (ret != 0) {

        printk("Failed to read register %x \n", CALIB00);

        return;

    }


    sensor_data_ptr->dig_t1 = ((uint16_t)values[1]) << 8 | values[0];

    sensor_data_ptr->dig_t2 = ((uint16_t)values[3]) << 8 | values[2];

    sensor_data_ptr->dig_t3 = ((uint16_t)values[5]) << 8 | values[4];

   

}


/* Compensate current temperature using previously stored sensor calibration data */

static int32_t bme280_compensate_temp(struct bme280_data *data, int32_t adc_temp)

{

    int32_t var1, var2;


    var1 = (((adc_temp >> 3) - ((int32_t)data->dig_t1 << 1)) * ((int32_t)data->dig_t2)) >> 11;


    var2 = (((((adc_temp >> 4) - ((int32_t)data->dig_t1)) *

          ((adc_temp >> 4) - ((int32_t)data->dig_t1))) >>

         12) *

        ((int32_t)data->dig_t3)) >>

           14;


    return ((var1 + var2) * 5 + 128) >> 8;

}

*************************************************************************

*/


int main(void)

{

    /* bme part begin

    *************************************************************************

    */

    static const struct i2c_dt_spec dev_i2c = I2C_DT_SPEC_GET(I2C_NODE);

    uint8_t regs[] = {ID};

    int ret = i2c_write_read_dt(&dev_i2c, regs, 1, &id, 1);

    uint8_t sensor_config[] = {CTRLMEAS, SENSOR_CONFIG_VALUE};

    ret = i2c_write_dt(&dev_i2c, sensor_config, 2);

    /* bme part end

    *************************************************************************

    */

    int err;

    uint32_t tx_handle = 0;

    uint32_t rx_handle = 1;

    uint32_t tx_counter_value = 0;

    uint8_t tx_buf[DATA_LEN_MAX];

    size_t tx_len;


    LOG_INF("Dect NR+ PHY Hello sample started");


    err = nrf_modem_lib_init();

    if (err) {

        LOG_ERR("modem init failed, err %d", err);

        return err;

    }


    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_callback_set(&dect_phy_callbacks);

        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_callback_set failed, err %d", err);

        return err;

    if (err) {

        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_init failed, err %d", err);

        return err;

    }


    k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_FOREVER);

    if (exit) {

        return -EIO;

    }


    hwinfo_get_device_id((void *)&device_id, sizeof(device_id));


    LOG_INF("Dect NR+ PHY initialized, device ID: %d", device_id);


    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_capability_get();

    if (err) {

        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_capability_get failed, err %d", err);

    }

    tx_counter_value = 0x7FFFFFFF;

    while (1) {

        /* BME PART BEGIN*/

        uint8_t temp_val[3] = {0};

        int ret = i2c_burst_read_dt(&dev_i2c, TEMPMSB, temp_val, 3);

        int32_t adc_temp =

        (temp_val[0] << 12) | (temp_val[1] << 4) | ((temp_val[2] >> 4) & 0x0F);


        int32_t comp_temp = bme280_compensate_temp(&bmedata, adc_temp);


        float temperature = (float)comp_temp / 100.0f;

        double fTemp = (double)temperature * 1.8 + 32;


        printk("Temperature in Celsius : %8.2f C\n", (double)temperature);

        printk("Temperature in Fahrenheit : %.2f F\n", fTemp);

        printk("Test %d",nrf_modem_dect_phy_time_get());

        /* BME PART END*/



        /** Transmitting message */

        LOG_INF("Transmitting %8.2f", (double)temperature);

        tx_len = sprintf(tx_buf,"%8.2f", (double)temperature);


        err = transmit(tx_handle, tx_buf, tx_len);

        if (err) {

            LOG_ERR("Transmisstion failed, err %x", err);

            return err;

        }


        /**tx_counter_value++; */


        /**if ((tx_counter_value >= CONFIG_TX_TRANSMISSIONS) && CONFIG_TX_TRANSMISSIONS) {

            LOG_INF("Reached maximum number of transmissions (%d)",

                CONFIG_TX_TRANSMISSIONS);

            break;

        }*/


        /* Wait for TX operation to complete. */

        k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_FOREVER);


        /** Receiving messages for CONFIG_RX_PERIOD_S seconds. */

        err = receive(rx_handle);

        if (err) {

            LOG_ERR("Reception failed, err %d", err);

            return err;

        }


        /* Wait for RX operation to complete. */

        k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_FOREVER);

    }


    LOG_INF("Shutting down");


    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_deinit();

    if (err) {

        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_deinit() failed, err %d", err);

        return err;

    }


    k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_FOREVER);


    err = nrf_modem_lib_shutdown();

    if (err) {

        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_lib_shutdown() failed, err %d", err);

        return err;

    }


    LOG_INF("Bye!");


    return 0;

}

Okay, let's adapt the DECT NR+ example to use two threads: one for reading the BME280 sensor and another for handling the DECT NR+ communication (transmit/receive). We'll use the concepts from the multi-threading example, specifically creating separate threads with their own entry functions and using a mutex for safe data sharing.

Here's how you can structure the code:

  1. Define Threads, Stacks, and Priorities: Add definitions for the new threads similar to the first example.
  2. Create Thread Entry Functions: Create two functions, one for the sensor logic (sensor_thread_entry) and one for the DECT logic (dect_thread_entry).
  3. Shared Data: Define a variable to hold the latest temperature reading that both threads can access.
  4. Synchronization: Use a mutex (k_mutex) to protect access to the shared temperature variable, ensuring one thread doesn't read it while the other is writing it.
  5. Move Logic:
    • Move the BME280 reading and compensation logic into sensor_thread_entry.
    • Move the DECT transmit/receive loop into dect_thread_entry.
  6. Modify main:
    • Perform all initializations (Modem, I2C, Sensor calibration) in main before starting the threads.
    • Start the two new threads using K_THREAD_DEFINE or k_thread_create.
    • main can then potentially exit or sleep, as the work is now done in the other threads.
  7. Data Exchange: The sensor thread will periodically read the sensor and update the shared temperature variable (locking the mutex first). The DECT thread will read the shared variable (locking the mutex first) before transmitting.

    // Check if this semaphore give is expected/needed. Often op_complete handles RX end.
    // If receive() duration ends naturally, op_complete should be called.
    // If nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx_stop() is called, this callback occurs.
    // Let's assume op_complete handles the semaphore give for now based on original code.
    // k_sem_give(&operation_sem); // Might be needed depending on exact flow
}

// --- DECT Transmit/Receive Functions (Unchanged logic, ensure device_id is available) ---
static int transmit(uint32_t handle, void *data, size_t data_len)
{
    int err;

    // Ensure device_id has been set in main before this thread runs
    struct phy_ctrl_field_common header = {
        .header_format = 0x0,
        .packet_length_type = 0x0,
        .packet_length = 0x01, // Example length, adjust if needed based on actual data?
        .short_network_id = (CONFIG_NETWORK_ID & 0xff),
        .transmitter_id_hi = (device_id >> 8),
        .transmitter_id_lo = (device_id & 0xff),
        .transmit_power = CONFIG_TX_POWER,
        .reserved = 0,
        .df_mcs = CONFIG_MCS,
    };

    struct nrf_modem_dect_phy_tx_params tx_op_params = {
        .start_time = 0, // Immediate start
        .handle = handle,
        .network_id = CONFIG_NETWORK_ID,
        .phy_type = 0,
        .lbt_rssi_threshold_max = 0, // Or specific threshold
        .carrier = CONFIG_CARRIER,
        .lbt_period = NRF_MODEM_DECT_LBT_PERIOD_MAX,
        .phy_header = (union nrf_modem_dect_phy_hdr *)&header,
        .data = data,
        .data_size = data_len,
    };

    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_tx(&tx_op_params);
    if (err != 0) {
        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_tx failed, err %d", err);
        return err;
    }
    LOG_DBG("TX submitted with handle %u", handle);
    return 0;
}

static int receive(uint32_t handle)
{
    int err;

    struct nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx_params rx_op_params = {
        .start_time = 0, // Immediate start
        .handle = handle,
        .network_id = CONFIG_NETWORK_ID,
        .mode = NRF_MODEM_DECT_PHY_RX_MODE_CONTINUOUS, // Or specific mode
        .rssi_interval = NRF_MODEM_DECT_PHY_RSSI_INTERVAL_OFF,
        .link_id = NRF_MODEM_DECT_PHY_LINK_UNSPECIFIED,
        .rssi_level = -60, // Example sensitivity
        .carrier = CONFIG_CARRIER,
        .duration = (uint64_t)CONFIG_RX_PERIOD_S * MSEC_PER_SEC *
                    NRF_MODEM_DECT_MODEM_TIME_TICK_RATE_KHZ,
        .filter.short_network_id = CONFIG_NETWORK_ID & 0xff,
        .filter.is_short_network_id_used = 1,
        .filter.receiver_identity = 0, // Listen for broadcast
    };

    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx(&rx_op_params);
    if (err != 0) {
        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx failed, err %d", err);
        return err;
    }
    LOG_DBG("RX submitted with handle %u for %u s", handle, CONFIG_RX_PERIOD_S);
    return 0;
}

// --- BME280 Functions (Unchanged logic, ensure spec and data pointers are valid) ---
#define CTRLMEAS 0xF4
#define CALIB00  0x88
#define ID       0xD0
#define TEMPMSB  0xFA
#define CHIP_ID  0x60
#define SENSOR_CONFIG_VALUE 0x93 // Check datasheet: Mode (e.g., Forced), Temp/Press oversampling

/* Get calibration data */
void bme_calibrationdata(const struct i2c_dt_spec *spec, struct bme280_data *sensor_data_ptr)
{
    uint8_t values[6];
    int ret = i2c_burst_read_dt(spec, CALIB00, values, 6);

    if (ret != 0) {
        LOG_ERR("Failed to read BME calibration data, err %d", ret);
        // Consider signaling failure if critical
        return;
    }

    sensor_data_ptr->dig_t1 = ((uint16_t)values[1]) << 8 | values[0];
    sensor_data_ptr->dig_t2 = ((int16_t)values[3]) << 8 | values[2]; // Signed
    sensor_data_ptr->dig_t3 = ((int16_t)values[5]) << 8 | values[4]; // Signed
    LOG_INF("BME T1: %u, T2: %d, T3: %d", sensor_data_ptr->dig_t1, sensor_data_ptr->dig_t2, sensor_data_ptr->dig_t3);
}

/* Compensate temperature */
static int32_t bme280_compensate_temp(struct bme280_data *data, int32_t adc_temp)
{
    int32_t var1, var2;

    var1 = (((adc_temp >> 3) - ((int32_t)data->dig_t1 << 1)) * ((int32_t)data->dig_t2)) >> 11;
    var2 = (((((adc_temp >> 4) - ((int32_t)data->dig_t1)) *
              ((adc_temp >> 4) - ((int32_t)data->dig_t1))) >> 12) *
            ((int32_t)data->dig_t3)) >> 14;

    return ((var1 + var2) * 5 + 128) >> 8; // Returns temperature in DegC * 100
}

// --- Sensor Thread Entry Function ---
void sensor_thread_entry(void *p1, void *p2, void *p3)
{
    int ret;
    uint8_t temp_val[3] = {0}; // Buffer for raw temperature reading
    int32_t adc_temp;
    int32_t comp_temp;
    float temperature_c;

    // Configuration: Set sensor mode (e.g., Normal mode, Forced mode) and oversampling
    // The original code wrote 0x93 to CTRLMEAS (0xF4) once in main.
    // This likely sets Temp/Press oversampling and puts it in Normal or Forced mode.
    // If Forced mode, we need to trigger a measurement before reading.
    // If Normal mode, it measures continuously. Let's assume Normal mode from 0x93.
    // Check BME280 datasheet for 0x93 meaning (likely osrs_t=2, osrs_p=5, mode=Normal/Forced). Assuming Normal for now.

    LOG_INF("Sensor thread started");

    while (1) {
        // Read raw temperature data
        ret = i2c_burst_read_dt(&dev_i2c, TEMPMSB, temp_val, 3);
        if (ret != 0) {
            LOG_ERR("Failed to read temperature register, err %d", ret);
            k_msleep(SENSOR_READ_INTERVAL_MS); // Wait before retrying
            continue;
        }

        // Combine raw data
        adc_temp = (temp_val[0] << 12) | (temp_val[1] << 4) | ((temp_val[2] >> 4) & 0x0F);

        // Compensate temperature
        comp_temp = bme280_compensate_temp(&bmedata, adc_temp);
        temperature_c = (float)comp_temp / 100.0f;

        // --- Update Shared Temperature Variable ---
        ret = k_mutex_lock(&temp_mutex, K_MSEC(100)); // Wait up to 100ms for mutex
        if (ret == 0) {
            g_current_temperature_c = temperature_c;
            k_mutex_unlock(&temp_mutex);
            LOG_INF("Sensor Read: %.2f C", temperature_c);
        } else {
             LOG_WRN("Could not lock temp mutex in sensor thread");
        }
        // -----------------------------------------

        // Wait before next reading
        k_msleep(SENSOR_READ_INTERVAL_MS);
    }
}

// --- DECT Thread Entry Function ---
void dect_thread_entry(void *p1, void *p2, void *p3)
{
    int err;
    uint32_t tx_handle = 0; // Use distinct handles if ops can overlap
    uint32_t rx_handle = 1;
    uint8_t tx_buf[DATA_LEN_MAX];
    size_t tx_len;
    float local_temperature_c; // Local copy of temperature

    LOG_INF("DECT thread started");

    // Optional: Get capabilities if needed after init (moved from main loop)
    // err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_capability_get();
    // if (err) {
    //     LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_capability_get failed, err %d", err);
    //     // Handle error - maybe cannot proceed
    // }
    // k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_FOREVER); // Wait if capability_get was called

    while (1) {
        // --- Read Shared Temperature Variable ---
        err = k_mutex_lock(&temp_mutex, K_MSEC(100)); // Wait up to 100ms
        if (err == 0) {
            local_temperature_c = g_current_temperature_c;
            k_mutex_unlock(&temp_mutex);
        } else {
             LOG_WRN("Could not lock temp mutex in DECT thread, using last known temp: %.2f", local_temperature_c);
             // Keep using the old local_temperature_c value
        }
        // ---------------------------------------

        // Format message for transmission
        tx_len = snprintf(tx_buf, sizeof(tx_buf), "T:%.2fC", local_temperature_c);
        if (tx_len >= sizeof(tx_buf)) {
            LOG_WRN("Temperature string truncated!");
            tx_len = sizeof(tx_buf) - 1; // Ensure null termination space
        }

        LOG_INF("Transmitting: %s", tx_buf);

        // Transmit message
        err = transmit(tx_handle, tx_buf, tx_len);
        if (err) {
            LOG_ERR("Transmission failed, err %d", err);
            // Decide how to recover, maybe sleep and retry?
            k_msleep(1000); // Wait a bit before retrying loop
            continue;
        }

        // Wait for TX operation to complete via op_complete callback
        err = k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_SECONDS(5)); // Add timeout
        if(err != 0) {
            LOG_ERR("Timeout waiting for TX complete (handle %u)", tx_handle);
            // Potentially try to stop the TX op or reset modem state
            // For now, just log and continue to RX attempt
        } else {
            LOG_DBG("TX complete confirmation received (handle %u)", tx_handle);
        }

        // Receive messages for configured duration
        err = receive(rx_handle);
        if (err) {
            LOG_ERR("Starting reception failed, err %d", err);
            // Decide how to recover
            k_msleep(1000);
            continue;
        }

        // Wait for RX operation to complete (either duration ends or error)
        // op_complete callback signals this semaphore
        err = k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_SECONDS(CONFIG_RX_PERIOD_S + 2)); // Timeout slightly longer than RX period
         if(err != 0) {
            LOG_ERR("Timeout waiting for RX complete (handle %u)", rx_handle);
            // Potentially stop RX forcefully: nrf_modem_dect_phy_rx_stop(rx_handle)
            // And wait for rx_stop callback's semaphore signal
        } else {
             LOG_DBG("RX complete confirmation received (handle %u)", rx_handle);
        }

        // Optional delay between cycles
        // k_msleep(500);
    }
    // Note: The loop above never exits in this example.
    // Cleanup code below main's thread start is unreachable unless threads exit.
}


// --- Main Function (Initialization) ---
int main(void)
{
    int err;

    LOG_INF("DECT NR+ PHY Multi-Threaded Sample Started");

    // --- Initialize Modem Library ---
    err = nrf_modem_lib_init();
    if (err) {
        LOG_ERR("Modem library init failed, err %d", err);
        return err;
    }

    // --- Initialize I2C Sensor ---
    if (!device_is_ready(dev_i2c.bus)) {
		LOG_ERR("I2C bus %s is not ready!", dev_i2c.bus->name);
		return -ENODEV;
	}
    LOG_INF("I2C device %s ready", dev_i2c.name);

    // Optional: Check BME280 Chip ID
    uint8_t chip_id_reg[] = {ID};
    uint8_t chip_id_val = 0;
    err = i2c_write_read_dt(&dev_i2c, chip_id_reg, sizeof(chip_id_reg), &chip_id_val, sizeof(chip_id_val));
    if (err) {
        LOG_ERR("Failed to read BME Chip ID, err: %d", err);
        // return err; // Decide if fatal
    } else if (chip_id_val != CHIP_ID) {
         LOG_WRN("BME Chip ID mismatch! Expected 0x%02X, Got 0x%02X", CHIP_ID, chip_id_val);
         // return -ENODEV; // Decide if fatal
    } else {
        LOG_INF("BME Chip ID OK (0x%02X)", chip_id_val);
    }

    // Get BME280 Calibration Data
    bme_calibrationdata(&dev_i2c, &bmedata);

    // Configure BME280 Sensor (e.g., oversampling, mode)
    uint8_t sensor_config[] = {CTRLMEAS, SENSOR_CONFIG_VALUE};
    err = i2c_write_dt(&dev_i2c, sensor_config, sizeof(sensor_config));
    if (err) {
         LOG_ERR("Failed to write BME config, err: %d", err);
        // return err; // Decide if fatal
    } else {
        LOG_INF("BME configured with value 0x%02X to reg 0x%02X", SENSOR_CONFIG_VALUE, CTRLMEAS);
    }


    // --- Initialize DECT PHY ---
    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_callback_set(&dect_phy_callbacks);
    if (err) {
        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_callback_set failed, err %d", err);
        // nrf_modem_lib_shutdown(); // Attempt cleanup
        return err;
    }

    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_init(&dect_phy_init_params);
    if (err) {
        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_init failed, err %d", err);
        // nrf_modem_lib_shutdown(); // Attempt cleanup
        return err;
    }

    // Wait for the init callback to complete
    err = k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_SECONDS(10)); // Wait for initialization
    if (err != 0) {
         LOG_ERR("Timeout waiting for DECT PHY init complete!");
         // nrf_modem_lib_shutdown(); // Attempt cleanup
         return -ETIMEDOUT;
    }
    if (exit_app) { // Check if init callback reported an error
         LOG_ERR("DECT PHY init failed in callback.");
         // nrf_modem_lib_shutdown(); // Attempt cleanup
         return -EIO;
    }


    // --- Get Device ID (after modem is up) ---
    // Note: Size must match destination buffer exactly for hwinfo_get_device_id
    uint8_t dev_id_buf[sizeof(device_id)];
    err = hwinfo_get_device_id(dev_id_buf, sizeof(dev_id_buf));
     if (err < 0) { // Returns bytes copied on success, negative errno on failure
        LOG_ERR("Failed to get device ID, err %d", err);
        // Handle error, maybe assign a default ID? For now, proceed cautiously.
        device_id = 0xFFFF; // Assign placeholder ID
    } else {
        // Assuming little-endian platform if copying bytes directly
        memcpy(&device_id, dev_id_buf, sizeof(device_id));
        // Or handle potential endianness issues if needed
    }

    LOG_INF("DECT NR+ PHY initialized, Device ID: %u (0x%04X)", device_id, device_id);


    // --- Start Worker Threads ---
    // Threads defined using K_THREAD_DEFINE below main

    LOG_INF("Starting worker threads...");
    // Main thread doesn't need to do anything else, the worker threads run the loops.
    // It could sleep, monitor thread health, or handle shutdown signals.
    // For this example, let main exit (the kernel keeps running the other threads).
    return 0;

    // --- Cleanup (Unreachable in this example as threads loop forever) ---
    // This part would only be reached if the threads had exit conditions
    // and potentially a mechanism for main to wait for them (e.g., k_thread_join).

    /*
    LOG_INF("Shutting down DECT PHY");
    err = nrf_modem_dect_phy_deinit();
    if (err) {
        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_dect_phy_deinit() failed, err %d", err);
    } else {
        k_sem_take(&operation_sem, K_SECONDS(5)); // Wait for deinit callback
    }

    LOG_INF("Shutting down modem library");
    err = nrf_modem_lib_shutdown();
    if (err) {
        LOG_ERR("nrf_modem_lib_shutdown() failed, err %d", err);
    }

    LOG_INF("Application finished.");
    return 0;
    */
}

// --- Thread Definitions ---
K_THREAD_DEFINE(sensor_thread_id, SENSOR_STACKSIZE, sensor_thread_entry, NULL, NULL, NULL,
                SENSOR_PRIORITY, 0, 0);

K_THREAD_DEFINE(dect_thread_id, DECT_STACKSIZE, dect_thread_entry, NULL, NULL, NULL,
                DECT_PRIORITY, 0, 0);

Key Changes and Considerations:

  1. Thread Creation: sensor_thread_entry and dect_thread_entry functions are created. K_THREAD_DEFINE macros are added at the bottom to create and start these threads automatically.
  2. Stack Sizes: Stack sizes (SENSOR_STACKSIZE, DECT_STACKSIZE) are defined. These might need tuning depending on your exact toolchain, logging level, and C library usage (especially floating-point operations in printk or snprintf). Start generous and profile if needed.
  3. Priorities: SENSOR_PRIORITY and DECT_PRIORITY are defined. The DECT thread is given higher priority (lower number) as it interacts with the time-sensitive modem.
  4. Shared Data & Mutex: g_current_temperature_c stores the temperature, and temp_mutex protects access to it. Both threads use k_mutex_lock() and k_mutex_unlock() around accesses to this variable. Timeouts are added to k_mutex_lock to prevent indefinite blocking.
  5. Initialization in main: All hardware setup (I2C, BME calibration, Modem Lib, DECT PHY init) is done sequentially in main before starting the threads. This ensures hardware is ready.
  6. DECT Callbacks & Semaphore: The DECT callbacks remain the same. They signal the operation_sem. The dect_thread_entry now takes this semaphore after initiating transmit and receive operations. Timeouts (K_SECONDS) are added to k_sem_take for robustness.
  7. Sensor Loop: The sensor_thread_entry loops, reads the sensor, compensates the value, locks the mutex, updates the global temperature, unlocks the mutex, and sleeps (k_msleep).
  8. DECT Loop: The dect_thread_entry loops, locks the mutex, reads the global temperature into a local variable, unlocks the mutex, formats the data, calls transmit, waits for completion, calls receive, and waits for completion.
  9. Error Handling: Basic error checks are included. In a real application, you'd need more robust handling (e.g., retries, resetting peripherals, signaling failures). Timeouts on semaphore and mutex waits help detect deadlock or peripheral hangs.
  10. Global Variables: Variables needed by threads or callbacks (like dev_i2c, bmedata, device_id, operation_sem) are made static global or moved to file scope.
  11. Cleanup: The original cleanup code in main after the loop is now effectively unreachable because the worker threads loop infinitely. A proper shutdown mechanism would require the threads to have exit conditions and main to potentially join them or respond to a shutdown signal.
  12. snprintf: Used for safer string formatting compared to sprintf.

Remember to adjust CONFIG_RX_PERIOD_S, CONFIG_TX_POWER, CONFIG_NETWORK_ID, CONFIG_CARRIER, CONFIG_MCS etc., in your prj.conf as needed.
